NEW EPISODE!! 🎤
Elaine Parker was stalked by a man she met on a dating app.
The relationship moved quickly, and right after they were engaged, Elaine endured domestic abuse, sexual assault, and rape. She finally got him out of the house and turned to the police, who arrested him multiple times when he began stalking her, threatening her, and trying to break into her home. As his stalking continued, Elaine found out he was still online dating and bragged about it on social media. While Elaine’s stalker is currently in prison, she has made it her mission to help others by creating Safer Date - a dating app that puts safety first. New members must pass mandatory ID checks, global criminal background checks, insolvency checks, and even addict register checks for added peace of mind. Elaine is here to talk about her fight for justice and how she’s become a survivor and an advocate for other women.

📍Dreamer Hostel, Santa Marta, Colombia 🇨🇴
When I travel I often stay in hostels rather than hotels… and people always wonder why 🤷🏼‍♀️ lots of reasons! 
▪️I travel solo & it’s way easier to meet people in a hostel. For example, if I want to take a day trip somewhere & don’t want to go alone or it might not be entirely safe to go alone (like hiking remotely) I can ask around and there’s always someone else going so I can tag along. 
▪️I’ve met friends for life in an evening of chatting & learned all about their travels & kept in touch. 
▪️People working in & staying in hostels are much more helpful, approachable & they keep an eye out for you to make sure you’re doing ok & make it back at night etc. so it’s a lot safer than a hotel for a solo female traveler like myself. 
▪️It’s much cheaper, but many hostels are more luxurious than the hotels! Gorgeous swimming pools, hammocks, bars, restaurants… while it depends on the country - I haven’t met a hostel I didn’t like anywhere in Central or South America.
▪️I get a private room & bathroom - just like at a hotel. 
▪️They often organize activities, tours, group outings, have laundry facilities, Wi-Fi, and really anything else you need!
▪️Am I older than most people who stay in hostels? Yup! Does anyone care? Nope! 😜

The iconic Puerto Rican Flag Door at 51 Calle San José, San Juan… 
Initially this door was painted the color of the Puerto Rican flag: red, white and blue in 2012. 
But on July 4th, 2016 the door was repainted black & white by Artistas Solidarixs en Resistencia, as a protest against the PROMESA law - signifying Puerto Rico’s financial crisis. 
Changing the colors meant the death of democratic values and the three government branches, the Legislative Branch, the Executive Branch, and the Judicial Branch, represented in the flag’s triangle. The black Puerto Rican flag door is a symbol of resistance and hope.

📍 Isla de Cabras (Goat’s Island), in Toa Baja, PR
I love doing a photo shoot in abandoned buildings… and this one has a story ☠️
Lazaretto de Isla de Cabras was a colony for the victims of infectious diseases was officially established on Goat Island & in 1876, construction began on four buildings that would serve as a shelter and hospital for the diseased. The brick structures were finished by 1883 and were known as the Lazaretto de Isla de Cabras. They housed the victims of yellow fever, cholera, and leprosy, among other diseases…. And admittance was pretty much a death sentence.
In 1923, the facility was forced to shut down due to its inhumane conditions.

“The World is Born in Every Kiss” or “El món neix en cada besada” in Catalan. Known to many as… The Kiss Wall 💋
This photo mosaic was designed by Joan Fontcuberta using images provided by local residents  asked to send in photos representing “a moment of freedom”. The resulting mural, made up of over 4,000 photographs on ceramic tiles, was installed in 2014 as part of Barcelona’s Tricentenary celebrations commemorating the fall of Barcelona during The War of The Spanish Succession.
“The sound of a kiss is not as loud as that of a canon, but it’s echo lasts a great deal longer.”
- Oliver Wendell Holmes

These mountains are home to the Benedictine monastery originally established around the 9th century, it was burned & looted in the Spanish Civil War in the 1930s and then rebuilt after & is home to about 80 monks. 
The Basilica is home to the Black Madonna, a revered religious icon who delivers miracles. 
Montserrat is a significant religious pilgrimage site, an architectural marvel, and the perfect place to spend a day.
It is said that there are inter-dimensional doors in the mountains, that people have been abducted by aliens here, and it is the location of the Holy Grail 🖤🇪🇸🖤
.

📍Park Güell, Barcelona 🇪🇸
